        • [ - ] tkr - member since 24-Aug-12

          @Yassine_1 Of course it wasn't. Typical of VAR to be so literal that it ignores the context of the play. A penalty is when a player deliberately breaks the rules to avert a goal or reasonable goal-scoring opportunity. If you keep your arms to yourself and the ball touches your arms, that's accidental and not a penalty. But the idiots running VaR take it so literally they will give a penalty every time. It's disguised as objectivity but is both anti-common sense and still subjective in "an I call as I'm paid" sort of way. Ask yourself if they would have called that penalty if it happened against Real Madrid or Barcelona.

          1 year ago
           +2 Reply Report Sign in or join us to rate comments! Sign In || Join Us
        • [ - ] tkr - member since 24-Aug-12

          @pyt55 All penalty calls are subjective, and it couldn't be any other way. Nor is there anything inherently wrong with that. The best we can aim for is that the referee's decisions dispense justice equivalent to the harm and do not alter the course of the game in an arbitrary way. To do this context is indispensable. If the ball was going wide the play is dead and it would be unjust to charge a penalty for some irrelevant technicality. The correct call would be to let the game continue with the corner. Instead, he decided for it to be a penalty. He didn't have to do that, it was a decision on his part, and no doubt another referee may have chosen differently. His decision effectively gave ManU the victory.

        • [ - ] tkr - member since 24-Aug-12

          @pyt55 We're not talking about retroactive justice. We're talking about how the purpose of a referee is to dispense justice in the moment and that the punishment must fit the crime. You don't give away the game in the last minute for a benign stupidity like that. This is what we'd call a SOFT penalty. If he did it on purpose, or if the shot was going in before he accidentally touched it, it would be clear as day, a HARD penalty. This one was not crystal clear, it was open to subjective judgment, and the referee gave ManU the game. I'm a neutral but I despise referees deciding games like this and it's hard to imagine than other fans of the sport could support it.
